code: # 1. Locate the installed extdata/ folder (contains only .RData now) path_extdata <- system.file("extdata", package = "BalanceMate")  # 2. Find all .RData (case‐insensitive) rdata_files <- list.files(   path_extdata,   pattern    = "\\.[Rr][Dd]ata$",   full.names = TRUE )  # 3. Convert each .RData to a .txt in a temp directory tmpdir <- tempdir() for (f in rdata_files) {   load(f)  # e.g. loads object “Postural_DataA” into your session   nm <- tools::file_path_sans_ext(basename(f))   write.table(     get(nm),     file      = file.path(tmpdir, paste0(nm, ".txt")),     sep       = ",",     row.names = FALSE,     col.names = FALSE,     quote     = FALSE   ) }   # 4. Merge from the tempdir Data <- Merge_PosData(   directory_path = tmpdir,                 SampleRate     = 100,   SessionDuration= 100 )  filtered_data <- Butterworth_it(   Data = Data,   cutoff_freq = 5,   filter_order = 2,   sampling_rate = 100,   type = "low",   Colname = c("CoP_X", "CoP_Y") ) # File names file_names <- c("Postural_DataB.txt", "Postural_DataA.txt", "Postural_DataD.txt")  # Loop through file names to generate plots side by side for (file in file_names) {   # Original signal plot   plot(     x = subset(filtered_data, filtered_data$file_name == file & filtered_data$Time > 30 & filtered_data$Time < 32)$Time,     y = subset(filtered_data, filtered_data$file_name == file & filtered_data$Time > 30 & filtered_data$Time < 32)$CoP_Y,     type = "l",     main = paste("Original Signal:", file),     xlab = "Time",     ylab = "CoP-Y"   )      # Filtered signal plot   plot(     x = subset(filtered_data, filtered_data$file_name == file & filtered_data$Time > 30 & filtered_data$Time < 32)$Time,     y = subset(filtered_data, filtered_data$file_name == file & filtered_data$Time > 30 & filtered_data$Time < 32)$CoP_Y_filtered,     type = "l",     main = paste("Filtered Signal:", file),     xlab = "Time",     ylab = "CoP-Y"   ) }

Quite counterintuitively, CoP-Y computed moments X-axis, CoP-X computed moments Y-axis. imagine Moments X-axis rotation bar orientated following X axis. title: Time_StampeR
text: Often times, several critical periods interest nested one session measurement. instance, researchers might created protocol including training phase, might used fixation crosses trial nested session, might blanks session, session might also include trials different types. , researchers might interested annotating data files highlight different periods interest. annotations facilitate data wrangling enabling easy filtering irrelevant data points (training, fixation crosses, blanks). Time_stampeR command enables annotations. use , understand structure data. sessions contain large quantity periods interest, using Time_stampeR might prove challenging, never impossible. cases researchers used randomisation stimuli presentation, users think outside box importing list characters used labels annotations. However, goes beyond demonstration. need help data wrangling process, can try contact author package. Nevertheless, Time_stampeR command can proves useful simpler cases (short sessions, periods interest, randomisation).

title: Time_StampeR

title: Managing, Pre-processing, And Processing Postural Data
text: BalanceMate package created facilitate handling postural data. tailored facilitate importation postural data exported using AMTI platform software Netforce. AMTI platforms force plates used research biophysics well psychology. Nevertheless, appear designed help practioners assessing patients individually without experimental protocol. Researchers, however, may find difficulties analyzing output NetForce software. particular: software allow merging individual data files one big data files software outputs minimal information: regarding bsf file designed analysed using BioAnalasysis prioritary software, data contains moments forces time course; data text format allowing computation different softwares, data contains moments forces stored unlabelled columns BioAnalysis software lacks flexibility allow computation postural indicators specified time intervals (.e., protocol includes training phase, AMTI softwares allow distinction two phases) BioAnalysis software offer transparency way postural indicators calculated. fact subtle differences moments forces .bsf outputs .txt outputs suggest undisclosed transformations occuring .bsf data AMTI team offers limited information regarding softwares (see mysterious point 4) BalanceMate package aims provide toolbox researchers recognise use AMTI forceplates softwares like use flexible transparent approaches manage, pre-process, process postural signals. However, note package can also used postural data collected using different platforms, long data frame containing: participants’ unique identifiers time course session Moments + Forces CoP-X + CoP-Y

title: Apply Butterworth Filter to Specified Columns — Butterworth_it
code: # Find subdirectory of Example data in the original .txt format exported from AMTI Netforce software # Note: we need to convert compressed rdata to original txt file files <- paste0("Postural_Data", LETTERS[1:6])  # Locate the directory containing the .Rdata files within the package data_dir <- system.file("data", package = "BalanceMate")  # Create a temporary directory to store the .txt files temp_data_dir <- file.path(tempdir(), "data") dir.create(temp_data_dir, showWarnings = FALSE)  # Process each file: load, optionally add a blank row, and write to .txt invisible(lapply(files, function(f) {   # Load the .Rdata file from the package's extdata directory   load(file.path(data_dir, paste0(f, ".Rdata")))    data <- get(f)   # Write the data to a .txt file in the temporary directory   write.table(data, file = file.path(temp_data_dir, paste0(f, ".txt")), sep = ",",   row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE) }))  Data <- Merge_PosData(temp_data_dir, SampleRate = 100, SessionDuration = 100)   filtered_data <- Butterworth_it(   Data = Data,   cutoff_freq = 5,   filter_order = 2,   sampling_rate = 100,   type = "low",   Colname = c("CoP_X", "CoP_Y") ) # Visualise results: plot(x = filtered_data[500:700,]$Time,       y = filtered_data[500:700,]$CoP_Y,       type ="l",       tck = 1,       main = "Non filtered")  plot(x = filtered_data[500:700,]$Time,       y = filtered_data[500:700,]$CoP_Y_filtered,       type ="l",       tck = 1,       main = "filtered")

what: Merge and Append your Postural data — Merge_PosData
title: Merge and Append your Postural data — Merge_PosData
text: function merges .txt files directly exported AMTI NetForce software. re-names columns (un-named AMTI software), compute automatically CoP antero-posterior (CoP-Y) medio-lateral (CoP-X) axes, add time course session facilitate data management. Finally, optionnally saves resulting output file directory. Note SessionDuaration argument optionnal serves purpose verifying data integrity: sessions different length, use . However sessions supposed equal length, might make sense use argument order assess whether number rows expected Sample rate Session duration match Actual duration sessions.

title: Merge and Append your Postural data — Merge_PosData
code: Merge_PosData(   directory_path,   SampleRate,   SessionDuration = NULL,   write_csv = FALSE )

title: Merge and Append your Postural data — Merge_PosData
text: directory_path directory folder containing .txt outputs AMTI Netforce wish merge single data set. SampleRate Sample rate used protocol SessionDuration Duration protocol (optionnal) write_csv Logical. TRUE, merged data saved CSV file directory. Default FALSE.

title: Merge and Append your Postural data — Merge_PosData
text: dataframe containing merged postural files, additional columns: CoP-Y, CoP-X, time course, file name.

title: Merge and Append your Postural data — Merge_PosData
code: #Find subdirectory of Example data in the original .txt format exported from AMTI Netforce software # Note: we need to convert compressed rdata to original txt file files <- paste0("Postural_Data", LETTERS[1:6])  # Locate the directory containing the .Rdata files within the package data_dir <- system.file("data", package = "BalanceMate")  # Create a temporary directory to store the .txt files temp_data_dir <- file.path(tempdir(), "data") dir.create(temp_data_dir, showWarnings = FALSE)  # Process each file: load, optionally add a blank row, and write to .txt invisible(lapply(files, function(f) {   # Load the .Rdata file from the package's extdata directory   load(file.path(data_dir, paste0(f, ".Rdata")))    data <- get(f)   # Write the data to a .txt file in the temporary directory   write.table(data, file = file.path(temp_data_dir, paste0(f, ".txt")), sep = ",",   row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE) }))  Data <- Merge_PosData(temp_data_dir, SampleRate = 100, SessionDuration = 100)

code: #Find subdirectory of Example data in the original .txt format exported from AMTI Netforce software # Note: we need to convert compressed rdata to original txt file files <- paste0("Postural_Data", LETTERS[1:6])  # Locate the directory containing the .Rdata files within the package data_dir <- system.file("data", package = "BalanceMate")  # Create a temporary directory to store the .txt files temp_data_dir <- file.path(tempdir(), "data") dir.create(temp_data_dir, showWarnings = FALSE)  # Process each file: load, optionally add a blank row, and write to .txt invisible(lapply(files, function(f) {   # Load the .Rdata file from the package's extdata directory   load(file.path(data_dir, paste0(f, ".Rdata")))    data <- get(f)   # Write the data to a .txt file in the temporary directory   write.table(data, file = file.path(temp_data_dir, paste0(f, ".txt")), sep = ",",   row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE) }))  Data <- Merge_PosData(temp_data_dir, SampleRate = 100, SessionDuration = 100)  # Compute mean SD CoP-X and mean SD CoP-Y at the participant (ID level): SD_CoP_ComputeR(Data, "CoP_X", "CoP_Y", "file_name") #> title: Compute mean Sway Path Length — SPL_ComputeR
text: data data frame CoPX_col column data frame storing CoP-X data CoPY_col column data frame storing CoP-Y data ID column data frame storing Participants' unique identifiers time_col column data frame storing Time course epoch_length numeric value: epoch duration want compute sway path length (seconds)

text: synthetised data frame (.e., shorter) additional column (Sway path lenght)

title: Compute mean Sway Path Length — SPL_ComputeR
text: specified epoch multiple protocol duration (e.g., user inputs epoch 3s protocol 10s), function compute SPL unbalanced time periods (latter example, 4 mean SPL computed three first periods corresponding 3s intervals, last one corresponding remaining time – 1s interval). warning issued inform user unbalanced epoch computations.

title: Compute mean Sway Path Length — SPL_ComputeR
code: # Find subdirectory of Example data in the original .txt format exported from AMTI Netforce software # Note: we need to convert compressed rdata to original txt file files <- paste0("Postural_Data", LETTERS[1:6])  # Locate the directory containing the .Rdata files within the package data_dir <- system.file("data", package = "BalanceMate")  # Create a temporary directory to store the .txt files temp_data_dir <- file.path(tempdir(), "data") dir.create(temp_data_dir, showWarnings = FALSE)  # Process each file: load, optionally add a blank row, and write to .txt invisible(lapply(files, function(f) {   # Load the .Rdata file from the package's extdata directory   load(file.path(data_dir, paste0(f, ".Rdata")))    data <- get(f)   # Write the data to a .txt file in the temporary directory   write.table(data, file = file.path(temp_data_dir, paste0(f, ".txt")), sep = ",",   row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE) }))  Data <- Merge_PosData(temp_data_dir, SampleRate = 100, SessionDuration = 100)  SPL_ComputeR(data = Data,     CoPX_col = "CoP_X",     CoPY_col = "CoP_Y",     ID = "file_name",     time_col = "Time",     epoch_length = 1) #>                        participant_id epoch sway_path_length #> Postural_DataA.txt.1   Postural_DataA     1        1.5983162 #> Postural_DataA.txt.2   Postural_DataA     2 title: Create a
text: function creates spaghetti plot - plot illustrates CoP displacements stored data frame. data frame contain minimally column storing time course, column storing CoP-X values, column storing CoP-Y values.

title: Create a
code: Spaghett(   df,   time_col = "Time",   copx_col = "CoP_X",   copy_col = "CoP_Y",   Title = "Spaghetti plot",   xlab = "Mean CoP_X",   ylab = "Mean CoP_Y" )

title: Create a
text: df dataframe containing data want plot time_col column dataframe indicates time course postural measurements copx_col column dataframe contains CoP-X displacements copy_col column dataframe contains CoP-Y displacements Title Character string specifying title plot (optionnal) xlab Character string specifying x-axis name (optional) ylab Character string specifying y-axis name (optional)

title: Create a
text: graphical object

title: Create a
code: data(Postural_DataA) # Load a session to plot Spaghett(Postural_DataA, time_col = "Time", copx_col = "CoP_X", copy_col = "CoP_Y") #> Error in Spaghett(Postural_DataA, time_col = "Time", copx_col = "CoP_X",     copy_col = "CoP_Y"): One or more specified columns do not exist in the dataframe.

what: Make a Spaghetti plot and draw an X% confidence ellipse area — SpaghettEllipse
title: Make a Spaghetti plot and draw an X% confidence ellipse area — SpaghettEllipse
text: function output -called 'spaghetti plot' indicating CoP-X CoP-Y movements specific time period, X% confidence ellipse area (default = 95%) spaghetti. 95% confidence ellipse circle 95% data points observed.

title: Make a Spaghetti plot and draw an X% confidence ellipse area — SpaghettEllipse
code: SpaghettEllipse(   df,   participant_id_col = "participant_id",   participant_id = NULL,   time_col = "Time",   time_start = NULL,   time_end = NULL,   copx_col = "CoP_X",   copy_col = "CoP_Y",   Title = "Spaghetti Plot with 95% Confidence Ellipse",   xlab = "Mean CoP_X",   ylab = "Mean CoP_Y",   conf_level = 0.95 )

title: Make a Spaghetti plot and draw an X% confidence ellipse area — SpaghettEllipse
text: df data frame containing data want output participant_id_col column data frame containing participants' unique identifiers participant_id character string: specific participant like plot (optionnal, specified, function plot participants) time_col column data frame storing time course session time_start numeric value: indicate start period want plot (optionnal, unspecified, function plot whole duration session) time_end numeric value: indicate end period want plot (optionnal, unspecified, function plot whole duration session) copx_col column data frame storing CoP-X data copy_col column data frame storing CoP-Y data Title optionnal character string customize title plot xlab optionnal character string customize x-axis plot ylab optionnal character string customize y-axis plot conf_level numeric value: Percentage confidence ellipse area (default = .95)

title: Make a Spaghetti plot and draw an X% confidence ellipse area — SpaghettEllipse
text: graphical object

title: Make a Spaghetti plot and draw an X% confidence ellipse area — SpaghettEllipse
code: # Find subdirectory of Example data in the original .txt format: # Note: we need to convert compressed rdata to original txt file files <- paste0("Postural_Data", LETTERS[1:6])  # Locate the directory containing the .Rdata files within the package data_dir <- system.file("data", package = "BalanceMate")  # Create a temporary directory to store the .txt files temp_data_dir <- file.path(tempdir(), "data") dir.create(temp_data_dir, showWarnings = FALSE)  # Process each file: load, optionally add a blank row, and write to .txt invisible(lapply(files, function(f) {   # Load the .Rdata file from the package's extdata directory   load(file.path(data_dir, paste0(f, ".Rdata")))    data <- get(f)   # Write the data to a .txt file in the temporary directory   write.table(data, file = file.path(temp_data_dir, paste0(f, ".txt")), sep = ",",   row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE) }))  Data <- Merge_PosData(temp_data_dir, SampleRate = 100, SessionDuration = 100)  SpaghettEllipse(Data, participant_id_col = "file_name", participant_id = "Postural_DataB.txt")

title: Annotate your Postural file to describe important periods — Time_StampeR

title: Annotate your Postural file to describe important periods — Time_StampeR
text: df data frame containing postural data id_col column data frame store participants' unique identifiers sample_rate sample rate used protocol protocol_duration duration protocols cuts list numeric values indicate protocol split distinguish two different periods. period_names list character strings used labels split. one label cuts.

title: Annotate your Postural file to describe important periods — Time_StampeR

title: Annotate your Postural file to describe important periods — Time_StampeR
code: # Find subdirectory of Example data in the original .txt format exported from AMTI Netforce software # Note: we need to convert compressed rdata to original txt file files <- paste0("Postural_Data", LETTERS[1:6])  # Locate the directory containing the .Rdata files within the package data_dir <- system.file("data", package = "BalanceMate")  # Create a temporary directory to store the .txt files temp_data_dir <- file.path(tempdir(), "data") dir.create(temp_data_dir, showWarnings = FALSE)  # Process each file: load, optionally add a blank row, and write to .txt invisible(lapply(files, function(f) {   # Load the .Rdata file from the package's extdata directory   load(file.path(data_dir, paste0(f, ".Rdata")))    data <- get(f)   # Write the data to a .txt file in the temporary directory   write.table(data, file = file.path(temp_data_dir, paste0(f, ".txt")), sep = ",",   row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE, quote = FALSE) }))  Data <- Merge_PosData(temp_data_dir, SampleRate = 100, SessionDuration = 100)  # here session: 30 s training, 3 trials (10 s fix cross + 90 s trial), 1s blank cuts = c(30, 40, 130, 140, 230, 240, 330) labels = c("Training",       "FixationCross",       "trial1",       "FixationCross",       "trial2",       "FixationCross",       "trial3",       "blank") Data <- Time_StampeR(df = Data,       id_col = "file_name",       sample_rate = 100,       protocol_duration = 100,       cuts = cuts,       period_names = labels)

title: Compute Postural indicators for specified time periods — compute_postural_indicators
text: data dataframe containing postural data CoPX_col column data frame storing CoP-X data CoPY_col column data frame storing CoP-Y data ID column data frame storing Participants' unique identifiers time_col column data frame storing Time course epoch_length numeric value: epoch duration want compute sway path length (seconds) indicators character string specifying postural indicator compute (can take multiple values). Possible values "CoP_X", "CoP_Y", "SwayPathLength", "EllipseArea", "SD_CoP_X", /"SD_CoP_Y".
